üí≤üí≤ It's Money Monday! üí≤üí≤

Each Monday, we will share financial aspects of the proposed bond and VATRE. Public school taxes are split into two different buckets that pay for two different sets of needs.

A VATRE only affects the M&O rate, while a bond affects the I&S rate. Visit nisdtxbond.org to learn more about public school taxes and the estimated impact on the tax rate.

post_text: The V.R. Eaton High School Percussion Ensemble has been selected as a winner of the 2020 Percussive Arts Society International Percussion Ensemble Competition. This is one of the highest honors a percussion program can receive in the world! This international success follows a regional victory this past spring when the EHS Percussion Ensemble received first place at the North Texas Percussion Festival in Forney, TX.

post_text: Congratulations to Northwest High School's Lisa Day on being named ESC Region 11 Secondary Teacher of the Year! Lisa and Fawn Rohrer, NISD Elementary Teacher of the Year, attended a special board room watch party for Region 11's virtual awards ceremony. Family and friends were able to celebrate the special event with along with Dr. Warren and district leadership. Lisa will now advance to the state level where she will compete for the Texas Teacher of the Year award. Congratulations to Lisa and all fellow educators nominated this year!

post_text:
Tarrant County Public Health and Human Services issued an order requiring school districts to begin the 2020-2021 school year with Remote Learning until September 28, 2020. This means that all NISD students (including those who live and/or attend school in Denton and Wise counties) will begin the school year as a Remote Learner.

Additional information will be shared during Dr. Warren's Facebok Live chat on Thursday at 6 p.m.

See the message from NISD Superintendent Dr. Ryder Warren here: https://conta.cc/2ZLCxZu

TEA issued this news release to the public this morning, and we expect more updates from state and local officials in the coming days. We appreciate everyone's patience and understanding as we review, process and work through our Return-to-Learn plans based on this latest information from TEA.

We received the information at the same time as the general public so we'll need some time to work through it and decide if/how this may impact our plans in NISD. Dr. Warren is still planning to send his regular Friday email update to families, so additional information may be shared during that communication later today.

post_text: Thanks to all of the individuals keeping us safe during the ongoing pandemic, including Commander Rick Coffman, the parent of a Byron Nelson student. Cmdr. Coffman shared the following message as he assists with efforts in New York: "To all of the seniors of 2020, you can endure anything in life if you can get through the trials on your first 'official year of adulthood.' Just when you don‚Äôt think you can make an impact, you show up in NYC during the very time that has put a halt to your senior year! I say it‚Äôs a sign! We are gonna fight this fight together. We are gonna win this fight together."

Update (9:30 a.m.): Oncor crews have restored power at all Wise County schools, and classes are proceeding as normal. Thanks to our students and families for their understanding and patience.

Original Post (8:15 a.m.): Prairie View and Seven Hills elementary schools as well as Chisholm Trail Middle School currently lack power, with electricians on site looking into the issue. Classes are proceeding as normal, as crews hope to restore power this morning.
text:
Update (9:30 a.m.): Oncor crews have restored power at all Wise County schools, and classes are proceeding as normal. Thanks to our students and families for their understanding and patience.

Original Post (8:15 a.m.): Prairie View and Seven Hills elementary schools as well as Chisholm Trail Middle School currently lack power, with electricians on site looking into the issue. Classes are proceeding as normal, as crews hope to restore power this morning.

post_text:
Update (9:40 a.m.): Oncor has restored power to Curtis Elementary School. Classes will resume at their regular time tomorrow, Sept. 27. Thank you to our Curtis Legends families for your understanding and patience during this situation.

Original Post (6 a.m.): Because of a power outage in the area, Curtis Elementary School will be closed today while crews work to restore electricity. The outage is expected to be resolved today, though Oncor crews inform us it will not be repaired in time for school. Families have been sent an email with this news and will be sent additional emails for any updates.
